voice_to_text: For a very long time, I've been ashamed of my scars. In my life, I've put somewhere near 1,000 of them on my body. I still struggle most days with that decision to add more. That idea that I can't ever be seen as normal or human again. But there are some days that I remember what I've gone through, what these have gotten me through. I'm not thankful for them, but I don't think I need to be ashamed of them either. Maybe instead, they can be something beautiful. Something more than what they began as. So I'm going to be making art from them today.

video_description: How are self injury and validation connected? #selfinjuryawareness #mentalhealth #childhoodemotionalneglect
voice_to_text: And so in your case, when you're talking about self injury and why is it so linked to validation, it's because we never got that. So I had many patients over the years who said that when they would, like, fall down and skin their knee, instead of a parent helping them clean it up and put a Band Aid on it, they were like, boys don't cry or girls don't cry, you know, brush it off, get up. Or. Or what are you whining about? The little scratch? Like, we're minimized, we're invalidated. We're told that it were too much, and we're left to take care of it ourselves. And I've heard some heartbreaking stories from my patients over the years of being too little to have to do this. Trying to bandage up their wounds or the wounds of their siblings, because parents weren't there, because they didn't tend to them, they didn't care to do what they really needed to do. And so we grow up thinking that no one else is gonna help us, that what we. That the validation we seek is too much. And so we try to express it this way. And that's why it feels like more and more and more with keep doing more and more and more, because, to be honest, it never feels like enough.

video_description: Here are some specific examples of healthy coping skills one can try to replace SH 1. **Journaling:** Write down your thoughts and feelings in a journal to help process emotions and gain clarity. 2. **Progressive Muscle Relaxation:** Practice tensing and relaxing different muscle groups to reduce physical tension and promote relaxation. 3. **Drawing or Coloring:** Use art as a form of self-expression and relaxation by drawing, coloring, or doodling. 4. **Listening to Music:** Create playlists of soothing or uplifting music to help improve mood and provide comfort. 5. **Engaging in a Hobby:** Dedicate time to activities you enjoy, such as gardening, cooking, or crafting, to distract yourself and foster a sense of accomplishment. 6. **Grounding Techniques:** Use sensory-based strategies like focusing on the present moment, describing your surroundings, or holding onto a comforting object to stay grounded during moments of distress. 7. **Practicing Gratitude:** Make a list of things you're grateful for or keep a gratitude journal to shift your focus towards the positive aspects of your life. 8. **Volunteering:** Help others in need by volunteering your time and skills, which can boost self-esteem and provide a sense of purpose. These are just a few examples, and it's important to explore different options to see what works best for you.  What coping skills resonate with you? video_description: Helpful tips: TIP#1 if you see a loved one with scars and you are already aware of their struggles with SH, do NOT point it out, and do not ask if they are new. If you are concerned, do it in a private place and make sure all parties involved are in the right headspace. TIP#2 if you see scars, and this person has never mentioned to you that they are struggling, you have a few options. 1: ask if the person is currently in any sort of crisis (in a private and safe space). 2: let them know that you are open to just listening, or even just a long hug. And 3: if the person does not want to open up to you, do NOT force them. And let them know that they have your support, and remind them that there are resources out there to help. Things will happen in that person‚Äôs own time, forcing things and rushing them will cause distress. TIP#3 If you are someone who doesn‚Äôt fully understand the psychology behind SH, consider educating yourself so you undertand where people are coming from. Have a great summer everyone!!! #fyp #educational #mentalhealthmatters #shscars #shisnotatrend #summer #shscarsandsummertime #notatrend
